{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775866506521,"sessionID":"ses_2861f8d58ffeA2I83Wpw4C47Gn","part":{"id":"prt_d79e380b6001bJvSmVOwLw1nam","messageID":"msg_d79e0844000127tQ5lCN8Dkqfs","sessionID":"ses_2861f8d58ffeA2I83Wpw4C47Gn","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_functions.write:1","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md","content":"# Proposal: Redis/Valkey Storage Implementation for Session Store\n\n## AR-013 — Redis Storage Implementation\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| **Module** | `pkg/store` |\n| **Language** | Go |\n| **Size** | M (Medium) |\n| **Status** | Proposed |\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement a persistent storage layer for sandbox metadata keyed by session ID, supporting both Redis and Valkey backends. The storage layer must:\n\n1. Persist sandbox metadata as JSON documents keyed by session ID\n2. Maintain secondary indexes for expiry-time and last-activity-time garbage collection\n3. Support atomic multi-operation transactions (pipelines) for data consistency\n4. Provide a unified `Store` interface that can be implemented by multiple backends\n5. Enable singleton access pattern for system-wide storage coordination\n\nThis implementation enables the agentcube system to track active sandbox sessions, perform cleanup of expired sessions, and identify inactive sessions for resource reclamation.\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope\n\n#### Core Store Interface (`pkg/store/store.go`)\n- Define `Store` interface with methods:\n  - `Ping(ctx context.Context) error` — connectivity verification\n  - `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID) (*types.SandboxInfo, error)` — retrieve by ID\n  - `StoreSandbox(ctx, *types.SandboxInfo) error` — atomic store with indexing\n  - `UpdateSandbox(ctx, *types.SandboxInfo) error` — update existing record\n  - `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID) error` — cleanup with index removal\n  - `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before time.Time, limit int64) ([]*types.SandboxInfo, error)` — GC query\n  - `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before time.Time, limit int64) ([]*types.SandboxInfo, error)` — activity query\n  - `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, sessionID string, at time.Time) error` — activity bump\n  - `Close() error` — graceful shutdown\n\n- Define package-level error: `ErrNotFound = errors.New(\"store: not found\")`\n\n#### Redis Implementation (`pkg/store/store_redis.go`)\n- `redisStore` struct wrapping `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` client\n- Connection via environment variables: `REDIS_ADDR`, `REDIS_PASSWORD`\n- Password requirement override: `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false`\n- Key patterns:\n  - Primary key: `session:{sessionID}`\n  - Expiry index: `session:expiry` (sorted set, score = ExpiresAt Unix)\n  - Activity index: `session:last_activity` (sorted set, score = last activity Unix)\n- Pipeline-based atomic operations for consistency\n\n#### Valkey Implementation (`pkg/store/store_valkey.go`)\n- `valkeyStore` struct wrapping `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` client\n- Connection via environment variables: `VALKEY_ADDR`, `VALKEY_PASSWORD`\n- Optional client flags: `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE`, `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE`\n- Same key patterns and semantics as Redis implementation\n- `DoMulti` for atomic batch operations\n\n#### Singleton Access (`pkg/store/singleton.go`)\n- `sync.Once`-protected initialization\n- `Storage() Store` — global accessor\n- `initStore() error` — provider selection and construction\n- Provider type constants: `redisStoreType = \"redis\"`, `valkeyStoreType = \"valkey\"`\n- Environment variable: `STORE_TYPE` (case-insensitive, defaults to `redis`)\n- Fatal logging via `k8s.io/klog/v2` on initialization failure\n\n#### Type Definitions (`pkg/common/types`)\n- `SandboxInfo` struct with JSON serialization tags\n- `SandboxEntryPoint` struct for endpoint definitions\n\n### Out of Scope\n\n- High availability / cluster mode configuration details\n- Advanced Redis/Valkey features (streams, pub/sub, Lua scripts)\n- Migration tooling from other storage backends\n- Metrics and observability instrumentation\n- Connection pooling tuning (use library defaults)\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Affected Components\n\n| Component | Impact | Notes |\n|-----------|--------|-------|\n| `pkg/store` | New package | Core storage implementation |\n| `pkg/common/types` | New types | `SandboxInfo`, `SandboxEntryPoint` |\n| Session GC worker | Consumer | Will use `ListExpiredSandboxes` and `ListInactiveSandboxes` |\n| Session lifecycle manager | Consumer | Will use `StoreSandbox`, `UpdateSandbox`, `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` |\n| Session activity tracker | Consumer | Will use `UpdateSessionLastActivity` |\n\n### Dependencies Added\n\n| Package | Purpose | Version |\n|---------|---------|---------|\n| `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` | Redis client | v9.x |\n| `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` | Valkey client | latest |\n| `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Logging | v2.x |\n\n### Configuration Surface\n\n| Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n|----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `STORE_TYPE` | No | `redis` | Backend selection: `redis` or `valkey` |\n| `REDIS_ADDR` | If STORE_TYPE=redis | - | Redis server address |\n| `REDIS_PASSWORD` | Conditional | - | Redis auth password |\n| `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Set to `false` to allow empty password |\n| `VALKEY_ADDR` | If STORE_TYPE=valkey | - | Comma-separated Valkey addresses |\n| `VALKEY_PASSWORD` | Conditional | - | Valkey auth password |\n| `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Set to `false` to allow empty password |\n| `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` | No | `false` | Disable client-side cache |\n| `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` | No | `false` | Force single-node client mode |\n\n### Performance Considerations\n\n1. **ZSET Range Queries**: Expiry and activity queries use `ZRANGEBYSCORE` with Unix timestamps; efficient O(log n + m) where m is result set size.\n\n2. **Pipeline Atomicity**: Store and delete operations use pipelined/multi commands to ensure primary key and index consistency.\n\n3. **MGET for Batch Loading**: Valkey implementation uses `MGET` for loading multiple sessions after ZSET query (requires keys in same slot for clustered deployments).\n\n4. **Nil Tolerance**: List loaders gracefully skip missing keys without failing the entire batch (handles orphan ZSET members).\n\n### Security Considerations\n\n1. **Password Policy**: By default, passwords are required. Use `*_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` explicitly for development/unauthenticated setups.\n\n2. **No Credential Logging**: Connection options must not log sensitive values.\n\n3. **Context Propagation**: All methods accept `context.Context` for timeout/cancellation control.\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: etcd as Primary Backend\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| **Pros** | Native Kubernetes integration; existing operator patterns; strong consistency |\n| **Cons** | Higher operational complexity; TTL enforcement less flexible; requires custom GC logic |\n| **Decision** | Rejected — Redis/Valkey sorted sets provide better native support for expiry/activity indexing |\n\n### Alternative 2: In-Memory Store with Periodic Snapshot\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| **Pros** | Simple; no external dependency; fast |\n| **Cons** | Data loss on crash; memory limitations; no distributed consistency |\n| **Decision** | Rejected — production deployments require persistence and high availability |\n\n### Alternative 3: SQL Database (PostgreSQL/MySQL)\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| **Pros** | ACID transactions; rich query capabilities; mature operational tooling |\n| **Cons** | Overkill for simple key-value + range query pattern; additional schema management; connection overhead |\n| **Decision** | Rejected — Redis/Valkey provide better performance for this specific workload (key-value with time-based range queries) |\n\n### Alternative 4: Support Only Redis (Single Backend)\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| **Pros** | Simpler codebase; single dependency; well-understood |\n| **Cons** | Valkey is an open-source Redis fork gaining traction; supporting both provides flexibility |\n| **Decision** | Rejected — dual support chosen for vendor flexibility and future-proofing |\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: Core Interface and Types\n1. Define `Store` interface in `pkg/store/store.go`\n2. Define `SandboxInfo` and `SandboxEntryPoint` in `pkg/common/types`\n3. Add `ErrNotFound` error definition\n\n### Phase 2: Redis Implementation\n1. Implement `redisStore` struct and constructor\n2. Implement all Store interface methods\n3. Add pipeline-based atomic operations\n4. Add environment-based configuration\n\n### Phase 3: Valkey Implementation\n1. Implement `valkeyStore` struct and constructor\n2. Implement all Store interface methods\n3. Add `DoMulti` atomic operations\n4. Add optional client flags support\n\n### Phase 4: Singleton and Integration\n1. Implement singleton pattern with `sync.Once`\n2. Add provider selection logic\n3. Add fatal error handling for initialization\n4. Write integration tests\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit Tests\n- Mock Redis/Valkey clients using `miniredis` or similar\n- Test each Store method independently\n- Verify error handling for missing keys\n\n### Integration Tests\n- Require running Redis/Valkey instance\n- Test full lifecycle: store → get → update → delete\n- Test ZSET-based queries for expiry and activity\n- Test concurrent access patterns\n\n### Configuration Tests\n- Test provider selection via `STORE_TYPE`\n- Test password requirement logic\n- Test Valkey optional flags parsing\n\n---\n\n## Risks and Mitigations\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|------------|--------|------------|\n| Redis/Valkey client library version conflicts | Medium | Medium | Pin versions in go.mod; use compatible versions |\n| ZSET orphan members during partial failures | Low | Low | List loaders skip missing keys; periodic full scan cleanup |\n| Connection pool exhaustion under load | Low | High | Use library defaults; document tuning parameters |\n| Key collision in clustered Valkey (MGET) | Low | Medium | Document deployment requirement for same-slot keys |\n\n---\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n1. ✅ All Store interface methods implemented for both Redis and Valkey\n2. ✅ `Storage()` singleton returns initialized store on first call\n3. ✅ `ErrNotFound` returned consistently for missing sessions\n4. ✅ Pipeline/multi operations ensure atomicity\n5. ✅ ZSET indexes correctly maintained for expiry and activity\n6. ✅ Environment-based configuration works as specified\n7. ✅ Integration tests pass against real Redis/Valkey instances\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- [Session Store Design](session-store/design.md)\n- [Session Store Specification](session-store/spec.md)\n- [client-go Library](deployment/client-go.md)\n- Redis Go Client: https://github.com/redis/go-redis\n- Valkey Go Client: https://github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go\n"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775866506513,"end":1775866506518}}}}
